I'm not convinced about this
CREATE TABLE BAR AS SELECT COUNT(*) FROM FOO GROUP BY ID;

It feels like the kind of thing a user would do by mistake, and then be puzzled why they couldn't access ID. IIUC current discussion is not to actually implement this proposal yet, just maybe in the future, if that's right then I am fine to push this debate to the future :)

I don't think we should do this, it seems like other sql systems keeps the duplicate columns:
postgres=# CREATE TABLE input (id VARCHAR, count INTEGER);
postgres=# CREATE TABLE in2 (id VARCHAR, cost INTEGER);;
postgres=# SELECT * FROM input JOIN in2 ON input.id = in2.id;
 id | count | id | cost
----+-------+----+------
 a  |     1 | a  |  100

Why do we need to introduce the special COPY function? With the changes in this KLIP, the key definition is inherited from the source in the FROM clause (unless we have a join, groupby or partition). Are the semantics that however many times a column (that is the key of the source) appears in the projection, every time it will be interpreted as the key? An alternative, which would be a bit more SQL like (in my mind at least) is to indicate the column that would be the primary key. So, something like:
CREATE TABLE OUTPUT AS SELECT PRIMARY(ID) , V0, V1, ID AS V2 FROM INPUT;

Just an idea though, not hung up on it. COPY gets the job done as well.

I am most worried about consistency:
Currently, the following is supported:
// transient
SELECT count(foo) FROM stream GROUP BY bar EMIT CHANGES;
// persistent
CREATE TABLE table AS SELECT count(foo) FROM GROUP BY bar;
Note, that the actual query SELECT count(foo) FROM stream GROUP BY bar is exactly the same for both cases.  This allows to deploy a transient query without any change as a persistent query.
With your proposal, the following inconsistency arrises:
// transient
SELECT count(foo) FROM stream GROUP BY bar EMIT CHANGES;
// fails -> PK missing
CREATE TABLE table AS SELECT count(foo) FROM GROUP BY bar;

// need to rewrite the query and add the PK `bar` to make it work
CREATE TABLE table AS SELECT bar, count(foo) FROM GROUP BY bar;
This seems to be issue with regard to UX, because transient queries and persistent queries would now support "different SQL".
Hence, if we require the PK in the transient query, we not only guide users away from writing "non-sense" (ie, not really useful) queries, but also avoid this inconsistency:
// transient -> fails
SELECT count(foo) FROM stream GROUP BY bar EMIT CHANGES;
// persistent -> fails
CREATE TABLE table AS SELECT count(foo) FROM GROUP BY bar;

// work both
// transient
SELECT bar, count(foo) FROM stream GROUP BY bar EMIT CHANGES;
// persistent
CREATE TABLE table AS SELECT bar, count(foo) FROM GROUP BY bar;

Another example:
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM S GROUP BY 1;
This is valid right now and will return the number of rows in the table, of the number of rows in the changelog.  Are we saying this should fail, because the key is not in the projection? We'd require them to do what?
SELECT 1, COUNT(*) FROM S GROUP BY 1;
Why????

Where does the name ID come from? It's not specified in the query via AS ID? Do you mean
CREATE TABLE OUTPUT AS
   SELECT ROWKEY AS ID, * FROM INPUT I1 JOIN INPUT_2 I2 ON I1.ID = I2.ID;
